  "abstract": "Abstract Clinical evidence synthesis largely relies on systematic reviews (SR) of clinical studies from medical literature. Here, we propose a generative artificial intelligence (AI) pipeline named to streamline study search, study screening, and data extraction tasks in SR. We chose published SRs to build , which contains 100 SRs and 2,220 clinical studies. For study search, it achieves high recall rates (Ours 0.711–0.834 v.s. Human baseline 0.138–0.232). For study screening, beats previous document ranking methods in a 1.5–2.6 fold change. For data extraction, it outperforms a GPT-4’s accuracy by 16–32%. In a pilot study, human-AI collaboration with improved recall by 71.4% and reduced screening time by 44.2%, while in data extraction, accuracy increased by 23.5% with a 63.4% time reduction. Medical experts preferred ’s synthesized evidence over GPT-4’s in 62.5%-100% of cases. These findings show the promise of accelerating clinical evidence synthesis driven by human-AI collaboration.",
